          "body": "The four-verse interlude on manna (11:7-9) is one of the Bible's subtler homiletical moves. Positioned immediately after the people dismiss manna as 'nothing at all' (11:6), the narrator pauses the story to describe manna carefully: its appearance like coriander seed and bdellium, its preparation methods (grinding, beating, boiling, baking), its taste like cakes baked with fine oil. The description is neither defensive nor sentimental — it is simply accurate. God's provision was rich, versatile, and daily renewed (11:9). The narrator is not answering the people's complaint; he is inviting the reader to see what the people were too hungry with ingratitude to see. This is the interpretive key to the chapter: the sin is not that the people were hungry. The sin is that they looked at genuine, miraculous, daily provision and called it nothing. As Charles Spurgeon observed of similar passages, unbelief does not merely err in its estimates — it systematically inverts them. Manna was the bread of heaven (Psalm 78:24); they called it worthless. The chapter's tragedy is located here, in the gap between what God was giving and what the people were willing to receive."
