          "title": "The quail that killed — when God's gift becomes His judgment",
          "body": "The provision of quail (11:31-33) is the chapter's most theologically disturbing episode. God does not withhold what the people demanded — He sends it in catastrophic abundance. A wind drives quail from the sea, covering the ground two cubits deep for a day's journey in every direction. The people gather for thirty-six hours straight; the minimum gathered was ten homers (roughly sixty bushels per person). And then: 'while the meat was still between their teeth, before it was chewed, the anger of the LORD was kindled against the people, and the LORD struck the people with a very severe plague' (11:33). The plague struck before the first swallow was complete. The theological message is precise and irreducible: God gave them what they craved and judged them for craving it. This is not paradox; it is the logic of Psalm 106:15 — 'He gave them their request, but sent leanness into their soul.' The same judgment-logic appears in Romans 1:24-26, where God 'gave them over' to what they desired as a form of wrath. God's gifts are not automatically blessings. Received with gratitude, they are means of grace. Demanded as entitlements from a Provider who is rejected in the demanding, they are instruments of discipline. The place-name says it plainly: Kibroth-hattaavah — the graves of craving."
