        "excerpt": "Now the people became like those who complain of adversity in the hearing of the Lord; and when the Lord heard it, His anger was kindled.",
        "body": "The chapter's opening clause contains the chapter's entire indictment: the people complained 'in the hearing of the LORD.' The Hebrew construction (*be-oznei Yahweh*, 'in the ears of Yahweh') is deliberate — the narrator signals that this is not casual grumbling but a complaint lodged before the divine throne. The Lord was present with Israel in the pillar of cloud (10:34); the people knew it; they complained anyway. This is what makes the opening fire (11:1-3) an act of justice rather than caprice.\n\nThe food-demand of 11:4-6 escalates the sin by specifying it. The 'rabble' (*asepesuph* — a mixed multitude of non-Israelites who left Egypt with Israel, Exodus 12:38) ignite the craving, but the sons of Israel join it. The list of remembered Egyptian foods (cucumbers, melons, leeks, onions, garlic) is historically plausible — Egypt's Nile delta was agriculturally rich. The theological problem is the comparative: 'but now our appetite is gone. There is nothing at all to look at except this manna' (11:6). The people have set Egyptian produce above God's daily miraculous provision.\n\nThe narrator's interlude (11:7-9) is his counter-argument: manna was not 'nothing.' Its appearance resembled bdellium (a fragrant resin mentioned as a precious substance in Genesis 2:12), its taste like fine-oil cakes. The gap between the narrator's testimony and the people's complaint is the chapter's central irony. It recalls the pattern Calvin identified throughout Israel's wilderness history: 'The more liberally God extends His benefits, the more His generosity is profaned by man's ingratitude' (*Commentaries on the Four Last Books of Moses*, Num. 11).\n\nMoses hearing 'the people weeping throughout their families, each man at the doorway of his tent' (11:10) completes the picture. The scene is communal, public, and organized — family-by-family weeping is a coordinated performance of dissatisfaction. God's anger burns greatly; Moses himself is displeased. The entire leadership structure of Israel — human and divine — is affronted by what is happening in the camp.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Asepesuph* (rabble, v.4) — from *asaph* ('to gather'); this mixed company is a gathered-together crowd of non-Israelites. *Nephesh* (our appetite, v.6) — literally 'our soul is dried up'; the word for the whole inner person is used, signaling that the craving is not merely physical hunger but a hollowing of the self. *Aph* (anger/nostrils, vv.1, 10) — the anatomical metaphor for a God who breathes hard with anger, a snorting nose; it recurs at the plague (11:33)."
